Yes, that's a common issue with browsers nowadays. It's called the "same-origin policy" and the "CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)" policy. This policy prevents a web page from making requests to a different domain, protocol, or port than the one the web page was loaded from.

In your case, your client ( probably running on port 3000) is trying to make a request to your server (running on port 8080), which is a different port. This triggers the CORS policy and prevents the browser from making the request.

To fix this issue, you need to add a response header to your server's responses that indicates which domains are allowed to make requests to your server. You can do this using the following middleware:

```javascript
const cors = require('cors');

app.use(cors({ origin: true }));
```

Just place this line of code before the router or middleware code block.

However, note that `origin: true` can be problematic if you're serving your application on multiple origins, as it can open your server to Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks.

A more secure and flexible way is to specify which domains are allowed to make requests to your server:

```javascript
const cors = require('cors');

app.use(
  cors({
    origin: [
      'http://localhost:3000', // specify allowed domains here
      'http://localhost:3001',
      // other allowed domains
    ],
  }),
);
```

This code will add an `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header to the response with the specified domain(s), allowing your client to make requests to your server.

Also, make sure that you add the `Access-Control-Allow-Methods` and `Access-Control-Allow-Headers` headers:

```javascript
app.use(cors({
  origin: [
    'http://localhost:3000',
  ],
  methods: [
    'GET',
    'POST',
  ],
  headers: [
    'Content-Type',
    'application/json',
  ],
}));
```

