In C#, you can convert the hexadecimal float value to a decimal floating point number using the BitConverter class. Here is how you can do it:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        uint hexValue = 0x3F800000;
        float floatValue = BitConverter.ToSingle(BitConverter.GetBytes(hexValue), 0);
        Console.WriteLine(floatValue);  // Output: 1
    }
}
```

However, since you already know that the hexadecimal value 0x3F800000 represents the float value 1.000, in a more simple way, you can directly use this value as float. In C#, when you use a numeric literal without any suffix (e.g., 'F', 'L', etc.), it will be treated as a float if possible. Since the hexadecimal value 0x3F800000 has more than 7 digits (it is a 32-bit float and C# compiler converts it automatically), it will be treated as a float. So, you can also do this:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        float floatValue = 0x3F800000;
        Console.WriteLine(floatValue);  // Output: 1
    }
}
```

You can simply print the float number using the Console.WriteLine method in C# like this:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        float number = 1.5f;
        Console.WriteLine(number);  // Output: 1.5
    }
}
```

If you want to format the float number with a specific number of decimal places, you can use the string.Format method or the $"{number:F2}" interpolated string syntax:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        float number = 1.5f;
        Console.WriteLine(string.Format("{0:F2}", number));  // Output: 1.50
        Console.WriteLine($"{number:F2}");  // Output: 1.50
    }
}
```

