To make the animation start from the bottom left and end at the top right, you need to adjust the positions in the `@keyframes trail` rule. The positions in the `drop-shadow` filter are given as `x offset` `y offset` `blur radius`.

Here's the adjusted code:

```css
.circle {
  fill: radial-gradient(white, lightblue);
  filter: drop-shadow(15px 15px 15px gray);
  transform: rotateX(15deg);
  transition: transform 0.3s ease-in-out;
  background: linear-gradient(to bottom, #fff, #ffcccc);
  box-shadow: 20px 20px 10px 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.75);
  border-radius: 90%;
  animation: trail 3s ease-in-out infinite;
}

@keyframes trail {
  0% {
    filter: drop-shadow(-30px 30px 30px gray);
  }
  100% {
    filter: drop-shadow(-15px -15px 15px gray) drop-shadow(15px 15px 15px gray);
  }
}
```

In the `0%` rule, I changed `drop-shadow(30px 30px 30px gray)` to `drop-shadow(-30px 30px 30px gray)`. Now the dropdown effect starts from the bottom left.

In the `100%` rule, I changed `drop-shadow(15px 15px 15px gray)` to `drop-shadow(15px 15px 15px gray)` and added `drop-shadow(-15px -15px 15px gray)` to create the effect of the shadow moving in the opposite direction.

