Unity is a unit testing framework that allows you to write unit tests for your code. Mocking is an essential concept in unit testing, as it allows you to isolate the dependencies of the code you're testing and focus on the specific functionality you want to verify.

To mock with Unity, you can use the `Mock` class from the `unityptest` library.

Here is a basic example of how to use the `Mock` class to mock a dependency in Unity:

```cpp
#include <unity/Dummy.h>
#include <unity/TestHarness.h>
#include <unity/Mock.h>

class MyDependency {
public:
    MyDependency(const std::string& value) : value_(value) {}

    std::string getValue() const {
        return value_;
    }

private:
    std::string value_;
};

TEST_FIXTURE(UnityTest, MyDependencyTest) {
    // Create a mock for MyDependency
    Mock<MyDependency> mock;

    // Set the expectation that getValue() will be called with a specific value
    EXPECT_CALL(mock, getValue())
       .WillOnce(Return("Mock Value"));

    // Create a MyDependency object that uses the mock
    MyDependency dependency(mock);

    // Test the code that uses the MyDependency object
    EXPECT_STREQ(dependency.getValue().c_str(), "Mock Value");
}
```

In this example, we're using the `Mock` class to create a mock object for the `MyDependency` class. We then set an expectation that the `getValue()` method will be called with a specific value ("Mock Value") using the `EXPECT_CALL` macro from Unity. Finally, we create a `MyDependency` object that uses the mock and test the code that uses the `MyDependency` object.

You can also use the `WillOnce` expectation to set the return value of a call. For example:

```cpp
EXPECT_CALL(mock, getValue())
   .WillOnce(Return("Mock Value"));
```

Or, you can use the `WillRepeatedly` expectation to set the return value of multiple calls:

```cpp
EXPECT_CALL(mock, getValue())
   .WillRepeatedly(Return("Mock Value"));
```

