In Tailwind CSS, `order-last` and `self-center` are utility classes that can be used to customize the layout of flexible items. Here's how you can use them:

**Order-last:**
`order-last` changes the stacking order of the flexible items. By default, the first item has an `order` value of 0, and subsequent items follow a sequential order (1, 2, 3, etc.). When you use `order-last`, the last item will have an `order` value of 1, while the subsequent items will have an `order` value that increments from the last item's `order` value.

```jsx
import React from'react';

function MyComponent() {
  return (
    <div className="flex">
      <div className="bg-blue-500 p-4 text-white">Item 1</div>
      <div className="bg-green-500 p-4 order-last">Item 2</div>
      <div className="bg-red-500 p-4">Item 3</div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

In the above example, the first item (`Item 1`) will have an `order` value of 0, the second item (`Item 2`) will have an `order` value of 1 (because of `order-last`), and the third item (`Item 3`) will have an `order` value of 2.

**Self-center:**
`self-center` is used to center a single item within its parent container without affecting the horizontal or vertical positioning of all the children.

```jsx
import React from'react';

function MyComponent() {
  return (
    <div className="flex">
      <div className="bg-blue-500 p-4 text-white flex-1">Item 1</div>
      <div className="bg-red-500 p-4 self-center">Item 2</div>
      <div className="bg-green-500 p-4">Item 3</div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

In the above example, the second item (`Item 2`) will be centered horizontally within its parent container because of `self-center`. The `flex-1` utility class is used to evenly divide the available space between the item and its siblings.

**Order-last + Self-center:**
When combining `order-last` with `self-center`, the second item will have its order increased, and it will also be centered within its parent

